Transcript by:

Aegerion Pharmaceuticals, Inc. (AEGR)Q2 2015 Earnings CallAugust 05, 2015 5:00 pm ETExecutivesAmanda Murphy - Associate Director-IR & Public RelationsSandford D. Smith - Interim Chief Executive OfficerEric Curtis - President, U.S. Commercial, Aegerion Pharmaceuticals, Inc.Mark Sumeray - Chief Medical OfficerGregory D. Perry - Chief Financial OfficerAnalystsTazeen Ahmad - Bank of America Merrill LynchEun K. Yang - Jefferies LLCEvan Seigerman - Deutsche Bank Securities, Inc.Morgan T. Haller - JPMorgan Securities LLCPhil M. Nadeau - Cowen & Co. LLCPresentationOperatorCompare to:Previous Statements by AEGR» Aegerion Pharmaceuticals' (AEGR) CEO Marc Beer on Q1 2015 Results - Earnings Call TranscriptGood day, ladies and gentlemen, and welcome to the Aegerion Pharmaceuticals' Second Quarter 2015 Earnings Call. At this time, all participants are in a listen-only mode. Later we will conduct a question-and-answer session, and instructions will follow at that time. As a reminder, this conference call is being recorded.I would now like to introduce your host for today's conference, Ms. Amanda Murphy, Associate Director of Investor Relations. Ma'am, you may begin.Amanda Murphy - Associate Director-IR & Public RelationsGood evening, everyone. Thank you for joining us today on our call to review Aegerion's financial results for the second quarter of 2015, and to provide a business update. I'm very pleased to introduce Aegerion's management team with us today, including new members on the call, Sandy Smith, Chief Executive Officer; Greg Perry, Chief Financial Officer; and Eric Curtis, President of U.S. We also have some familiar names with us today, including Martha Carter, Chief Regulatory Officer; Mark Sumeray, Chief Medical Officer; and Anne Marie Cook, Senior Vice President, General Counsel. At the conclusion of the prepared remarks, we will open the call up for questions.Please note that we have slides posted in conjunction with the webcast that supplement some of the information we will be discussing during today's call. These slides can be found on the Investor Relations section of our website under the Events & Presentations tab. If you are following along, please turn to slide two.Before we begin, please remember we will be making certain forward-looking statements on today's call, which includes statements regarding our forecasted future financial and operating results, the commercial potential and growth and value creation opportunity for our products and business, our ability to impact commercial metrics, the potential timing and outcome of pricing and reimbursement decisions outside the U.S., the potential for named patient sales and future approvals, the potential impact of competitive products and our planned commercial, regulatory label expansion, business development and clinical development activities, and anticipated impact and results of such activities, as well as other statements which relate to future events. These statements are based on the beliefs and expectations of management as of today.Our business is subject to risks, uncertainties and assumptions that are difficult to predict, and our actual results may differ materially from our expectations. Investors should read carefully the risks and uncertainties described in our earnings release and in our reports filed with the SEC, including the Risk Factors section of our Form 10-Q filed on May 8, 2015, available on the SEC's website at sec.gov. We assume no obligation to revise or update forward-looking statements whether as a result of new information, future events or otherwise. Also during this call, we will discuss non-GAAP operating results and guidance. The difference between GAAP and non-GAAP operating results and guidance is addressed in today's earnings release.At this time, it's my pleasure to turn the call over to Aegerion's CEO, Sandy Smith.Sandford D. Smith - Interim Chief Executive OfficerHi, everyone and thank you very much for joining today. I'd like to ask you to turn the page to the next chapter in Aegerion's journey. Having served on the board since 2012, I'm pleased to have the opportunity to lead Aegerion into this next stage of our mission, which remains the same as before, and that is to bring innovative therapies to patients with debilitating rare diseases. With the resources we have in place, we have the opportunity to successfully transition Aegerion to its next phase of growth. On my watch, I'd like to articulate some of the objectives that I will be pursuing with the management group.Number one, continuing to optimize the U.S. business for both of our products. Number two, expanding our global footprint through entering into new international markets. Number three, gaining reimbursement in European markets for lomitapide. And number four, deepening our product pipeline through both lifecycle management of existing assets balanced appropriately with business development activities. Ultimately, we believe success in any one of these areas has the potential of driving value for all of you, and I do plan to execute. I look forward to meeting with you personally in the near future as we can talk about the progress of moving towards these goals.So turning to slide three, what excites me as I contemplate the growth opportunities for Aegerion is a highly capable team and a supporting infrastructure that can be leveraged to support additional products. While managing through significant learnings about JUXTAPID in HoFH, we're proud to have successfully launched our second product MYALEPT. This enables us to leverage the people, processes, and systems already in place. And this leverage is important to us, particularly, as we bring a second product to our sales force existing both in the United States and in international markets.We're off to a strong start with MYALEPT. We continue to believe that the acquisition of MYALEPT was a sound, strategic decision. With significant growth in MYALEPT net product sales in the U.S., we made good progress in opening a new market for the treatment of generalized lipodystrophy. The product, as we expected, is behaving like a classic orphan drug as compared to JUXTAPID. The symptomatic nature of generalized lipodystrophy and the distinguished physical characteristics help to identify GL patients and create quite a predictable market. The challenge for MYALEPT is patient identification, and this is in our wheelhouse. With a leadership team and a sales force that brings significant orphan drug business experience, we're well positioned to grow MYALEPT.Read the rest of this transcript for free on seekingalpha.com

































